prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Early Measurement of the Continuum Flux
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We will measure the continuum flux in the inner coma of comet Siding Spring in order to determine the fraction of large grains in the inner coma surrounding the nucleus. We request observations to be planned around July 1st, giving us enough time margin to implement the measurement in our risk assesment for the Mars orbiters.

prj:TemporalParameters.prj:note: The first science goal (continuum measurement) should be executed around 2014/7//1.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
To estimate the continuum flux density of comet Siding Spring, we took the JCMT observations of comet Hyakutake (Jewitt and Matthews 1997, AJ, 113, 1145) and scaled them to reproduce the circumstances of Siding Spring. We accounted for the relative optical brightness of each comet, the Earth-comet distances, the temperatures of the dust for each comet's heliocentric distance, and the wavelength dependent beam sizes of the JCMT and ALMA (compact configuration C34-1).
As this is an absolute measurement of the flux that will be compared to measurements in the infrared, we request a signal to noise of 10.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Mapping of HCN during Mars closest approach
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We will measure the morphology and velocity field of HCN J(1-0) emission during the comet's close approach to Mars. We will monitor the comet for 10h to search for variability of the HCN jets, which will allow us to map them to the comet's nucleus.

prj:MonitoringConstraint.prj:note:
We request 5 exposures of 2h each to monitor the variability of the HCN emission. Mars obiter data will give us the rotational period of the comet. Here we aim to observe changes in the surface activity over a reasonable fraction of a rotation period.
These observations should be scheduld around the comet's closest approach to Mars. We are aware of the scheduling window of 7 days before/after our requested date. while we would most prefer observations on Oct. 20, any date within the 14 day window is close enough to the Mars observations that are confident in being able to extrapolate the comets' state of activity to the time of our observations.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
To estimate the line flux density of comet Siding Spring we took the IRAM observations of comets 103P Hartley 2 (Boissier et al. 2014, Icarus 228, p197) and C/2006 W3 Christensen (Bockelee-Morvan et al. 2010, A&A 518, L149), and scaled both to reproduce the circumstances of Siding Spring. We accounted for the geocentric distance, assumed a linear increase of the flux with solid angle, and assumed a HCN production rate of 5e26/s at an heliocentric distance of 1.4 AU based on its current brightness estimate (Horizons, Jorda et al. ACM 2008). As we are investigating the variation of the morphology of the comet, a signal-to-noise of 5 at the peak of the line is sufficient.
The time estimate is based on maximum signal to noise. Spatial information at higher spatial resolution will be present and will allow us to look at smaller beam sizes if the signal to noise permits us.
We will coadd all 10 hours to locate the precise center of the nucleus, which we expect to be detected at an SNR of 6 to 10 in this band (see science goal 1).

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Comet C/2013 A1 (Siding Spring) is a dynamically new comet that will pass within 135,000 km of Mars. This will allow the instruments on board Mars spacecraft to directly image the nucleus of an Oort Cloud comet on its first passage through the inner solar system with a resolution of 150 meter per pixel. We request interferometric observations of the continuum of comet Siding Spring to first measure the fraction of millimeter-sized grains in the coma to timely assess their hazard to Mars orbiters. During the closest approach to Mars, we propose to repeatedly measure the distribution and velocity field of HCN. HCN sublimates directly from the nucleus and its lines are the brightest cometary emission lines in wavelengths covered by ALMA. Combining our observations with the high resolution imagery and shape models acquired by the Mars orbiters will allow us to connect the jet activity of the comet to its surface.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Circumstellar disks, exoplanets and the solar system
